{{Use Australian English|date=November 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox recurring event | logo = Brisbane Open House logo.jpg | genre = Open day | frequency = Annual | location =[[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]] | first = {{start date|df=yes|2010|October|2}} | next = 7–8 October 2017 | participants = 100 buildings | attendance = 33,000 | website ={{url|http://www.brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/|brisbaneopenhouse.com.au}} | footnotes = }} '''Brisbane Open House''' is a [[Doors Open Days]] event held in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] that showcases many of the city's buildings to the public. Among the buildings included are historical landmarks, galleries, office buildings, museums, places of worship and bridges. Well known buildings not usually open to the public are open for free public tours. The annual event is usually held on the first weekend in October.
The event is organised by the [[Queensland Government Architect]], the Brisbane Development Association, and the [[National Trust of Queensland]].<ref name="kgbo">{{cite news| title =Brisbane Open House| work =| publisher =Brisbane Development Association| date =| url =http://www.bda.org.au/files/pictures/BDA%2009-10%20Year%20in%20Review%20-%20FINAL%20.pdf| accessdate =3 December 2010| deadurl =yes| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110706124242/http://www.bda.org.au/files/pictures/BDA%2009-10%20Year%20in%20Review%20-%20FINAL%20.pdf| archivedate =6 July 2011| df =dmy-all}}</ref>
Brisbane Open House is part of the ''Open House Worldwide'' annual cultural event.<ref>{{cite news | title =Brisbane Open House| work =| publisher =Green Building Council of Australia| date = | url =http://www.gbca.org.au/events.asp?eventid=32039&source=events-listing| accessdate = 4 October 2012}}</ref>
==History== The inaugural Brisbane Open House took place on 2 October 2010, and featured 20 buildings<ref name="bam">{{Cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/brisbanes-architectural-marvels-revealed-in-open-house-scheme/story-e6frfkp9-1225932428761?from=public_rss |title=Brisbane's architectural marvels revealed in Open House scheme |author=Phil Hammond |accessdate=27 September 2013 |date=1 October 2010 |newspaper=The Courier Mail |publisher=Queensland Newspapers }}</ref> in the [[Brisbane central business district|CBD]] and [[South Bank, Queensland|South Bank]]. More than 12,000 people attended. In 2011 the event expanded to 30 buildings and included [[Fortitude Valley, Queensland|Fortitude Valley]]. The 2012 event featured 51 buildings and attracted 33,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/|title =2012 Brisbane Open House|last = |first = |date = |work = |publisher =brisbane open house |accessdate =14 February 2013}}</ref> The 2013 event expanded to 71 buildings presented over a two-day weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/2013-buildings|title =2013 Brisbane Open House|last =|first =|date =|work =|publisher =brisbane open house|accessdate =11 September 2013|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130909050807/http://brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/2013-buildings|archivedate =9 September 2013|df =dmy-all}}</ref> The 2014 event featured 89 buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/2014-buildings|title =BOH 2014 Buildings|last =|first =|date =|work =|publisher =Brisbane Open House|accessdate =11 September 2014|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140911105439/http://brisbaneopenhouse.com.au/2014-buildings|archivedate =11 September 2014|df =dmy-all}}</ref> ===2016=== The 2016 event expanded to 100 buildings with large number of new buildings open to the general public for the first time: *[[480 Queen Street]] *[[Brisbane Arts Theatre]] *[[Fort Lytton Historic Military Precinct]] *[[Bertholme|Moreton Club]] *[[Queensland State Archives]] *[[Sir Thomas Brisbane Planetarium]] *[[Camp Columbia (Wacol)|Wacol Military Museum]] *[[Wolston House]]
===2015=== New buildings open to the general public for the first time were: *[[Archerfield Airport]] *[[Brisbane GPO]] *[[Princess Theatre, Woolloongabba|Princess Theatre]] *[[Queensland Fire and Emergency Services|Queensland Emergency Operations Centre]]
