'''Ira Chernus''' (born October 29, 1946) is a journalist, author, and Professor of [[religious studies|Religious Studies]] at the [[University of Colorado–Boulder|University of Colorado, Boulder]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://rlst.colorado.edu/Faculty/Ira-Chernus/# |title=University of Colorado at Boulder - Ira Chernus {{!}} Faculty |access-date=2011-04-14 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110826065123/http://rlst.colorado.edu/Faculty/Ira-Chernus/# |archive-date=2011-08-26 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> He received his Ph.D. in Religion from Temple University, specializing in the history of rabbinic Judaism. His academic writing now focuses on the foreign policy of US presidents. He has published books on Dwight Eisenhower and George W. Bush and is currently writing a book on Franklin D. Roosevelt. As a journalist, he has written extensively on peace, war, foreign policy, and nationalism in the [[United States]], as well as the Israel-Palestine conflict and U.S. Middle East policy. He has written often for the [[Huffington Post]],<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ira-chernus Ira Chernus]</ref> [[CommonDreams]], TomDispatch,<ref>[http://www.tomdispatch.com/authors/irachernus Ira Chernus {{!}} Authors {{!}} TomDispatch]</ref> [[AlterNet]],<ref>[http://www.alternet.org/authors/5734/ Ira Chernus | AlterNet]</ref> [[Truthout]], [[Foreign Policy In Focus]], and [[Religion Dispatches]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.religiondispatches.org/authors/irachernus/# |title=Ira Chernus {{!}} Bloggers {{!}} Religion Dispatches |access-date=2011-04-14 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20120908022558/http://www.religiondispatches.org/authors/irachernus/# |archive-date=2012-09-08 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> In 2012 he started a new blog, MythicAmerica.us,<ref>[http://www.mythicamerica.us/ Ira Chernus {{!}} MythicAmerica]</ref> and published online MythicAmerica: Essays.<ref>[http://mythicamerica.wordpress.com/ Ira Chernus {{!}} MythicAmerica: Essays]</ref> His recent writings on Israel, Palestine, and the U.S. are also collected on a separate blog.<ref>[http://chernus.wordpress.com/ Ira Chernus | Blog ]</ref> Many of his earlier writings can be found on his University of Colorado website.<ref>[http://spot.colorado.edu/~chernus/ Ira Chernus {{!}} Website]</ref> He has lectured in Lebanon, Finland, Australia, and Canada, as well as extensively throughout the United States.
