{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}} {{Use British English|date=December 2014}} '''John Albert Bullbrook''' (1882–1967; born in the [[Medway]] area in what was then [[Kent]] in [[South-East England]]) was an author, [[archaeologist]] and archaeological historian, who went to [[Trinidad]] in 1913 as a petroleum geologist. He began his archaeological career in 1919, pioneering the search on the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous population]] of Trinidad.
By the early 1930s, he already provides evidence of the prominence of reflections on the indigenous history of Trinidad, and on the figure of the [[Island Caribs|Carib]], in some of the élites’ writings of local history.
Famously in a public lecture in 1938, John Bullbrook, by then a local specialist in the [[Amerindian]] history of Trinidad, made the comment: "To this day we speak of the Queen if the Caribs at Arima, yet I doubt if there is much--if any--Carib blood in her race.".<ref name="Bul40"/>{{rp|p.4}}
In 1940, for a public lecture and book published under the Royal Victoria Museum and the Historical Society of Trinidad and Tobago, entitled ''The Ierian Race'', Bullbrook wrote: "Probably, if I were to ask any of my audience this evening what was the predominant or even the only race in Trinidad at the time of the discovery by Cristobal Colon, the reply would be unhesitatingly: ‘Why, Carib, of course’".<ref name="Bul40"/>{{rp|p.1}}
Throughout the 1940s, he conducted extensive excavations in the Amerindian middens in Cedros, Erin and [[Palo Seco, Trinidad|Palo Seco]]. The Cedros site in Trinidad, which he excavated with Irving Rouse in 1946, is considered one of the most important archaeological sites in the Caribbean, consisting of a partly destroyed shell midden located on the southwest tip of Trinidad. The corrected radiocarbon datings for the finds at this site were given as 190 B.C. and A.D. 100.<ref name="Bul53"/>{{rp|pp.96–97, 101–105, 109–110}}
Bullbrook, as a partisan in the local debate over whether the true natives of Trinidad were Carib or [[Arawak]], lamented later, in 1960, that the "tradition" of believing that Caribs were the indigenous people of Trinidad was "deep rooted and hard to destroy".<ref name="Bul60"/>{{rp|pp.54–55}}
In July 1960, Bullbrook, at the first conference in the [[Caribbean|West Indies]] on [[pre-Columbian|pre-Columbian archaeology]] held in [[Fort-de-France]], [[Martinique]], discussed his research into the "Arawaks and Caribs of Trinidad" along with the likes of Rev. Father Pinchon and A. H. Anderson. Articles of Bullbrook's have been published in magazines with a varying range of readers such as ''The Caribbean'', ''Caribbean Quarterly'', and ''Shell Magazine''.<ref name="Mid60"/>{{rp|p.1}}
He later became [[curator]] of the Royal Victoria Institute (now the [[National Museum and Art Gallery, Trinidad|National Museum]]), and died at the age of 85 (in 1967).
John Bullbrook (who was the first to use modern stratigraphic techniques in Trinidad), having been educated in Great Britain, had previous field experience in the Anglo-Egyptian Sudan. His techniques represent a significant advance over the ‘[[Museology|museological]]’ approach that characterized the work of [[Jesse Walter Fewkes|Fewkes (1850–1930)]] and [[Theodoor de Booy|de Booy (1882–1919)]].<ref name="Fig74"/>
His collection of correspondence with [[Yale University]] (1941–1963), with a variety of people on the subject of archaeology in the West Indies (1917–1960), with the Historical Society of Trinidad and Tobago (1939–1949); and correspondence with the Trinidad and Tobago Field Naturalists Club, have all been donated to the [[University of the West Indies]] by Carlisle Chang (in October 2000).
Bullbrook was [[homosexual]], but was [[lavender marriage|married]] to the lesbian painter [[Amy Leong Pang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2013-01-15/will-you-be-my-beard|title=Will you be my beard?|work=The Trinidad Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>
